=========================================
C++ MULTIMAP (Associative Container)
INTERVIEW PREPARATION NOTES
=========================================

1. What is multimap?
--------------------

std::multimap is an associative container that stores:

key -> value

Unlike map:

✓ Duplicate keys allowed
✓ Keys automatically sorted

Example:

multimap<int,string> mm;

mm.insert({1,"John"});
mm.insert({1,"David"});

Output:

1 -> John
1 -> David

-----------------------------------------

2. Internal Implementation
--------------------------

Implemented using:

Red-Black Tree
(Self-Balancing BST)

Properties:

✓ Sorted keys
✓ Duplicate keys allowed
✓ Search O(log n)
✓ Insert O(log n)
✓ Delete O(log n)

Interview Q:
How is multimap implemented internally?

Answer:
std::multimap is typically implemented using a Red-Black Tree that allows multiple elements with the same key.

-----------------------------------------

3. Key Characteristics
----------------------

✓ Key-Value storage
✓ Duplicate keys allowed
✓ Sorted by key
✓ O(log n) operations

Example:

multimap<int,string> mm;

mm.insert({10,"A"});
mm.insert({10,"B"});
mm.insert({20,"C"});

Output:

10 A
10 B
20 C

-----------------------------------------

4. Difference Between map and multimap
--------------------------------------

map
---
Duplicate Keys:
✗ Not Allowed

multimap
--------
Duplicate Keys:
✓ Allowed

Example:

map<int,string>

1 -> A
1 -> B

Result:

1 -> B

Old value overwritten.

-----------------------------------------

multimap<int,string>

1 -> A
1 -> B

Result:

1 -> A
1 -> B

Both stored.

Interview Q:
Difference between map and multimap?

Answer:
map stores unique keys, whereas multimap allows multiple elements with the same key.

-----------------------------------------

5. Complexity
-------------

insert()            O(log n)

find()              O(log n)

erase()             O(log n)

count()             O(log n + k)

equal_range()       O(log n)

lower_bound()       O(log n)

upper_bound()       O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

6. Why No operator[]?
---------------------

Not supported.

Reason:

Multiple values may exist for the same key.

Therefore:

mm[10];   // ERROR

Interview Q:
Why doesn't multimap support operator[]?

Answer:
Because duplicate keys are allowed, there is no unique value associated with a key.

-----------------------------------------

7. insert()
-----------

mm.insert({1,"John"});

mm.insert({1,"David"});

Complexity:

O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

8. find()
---------

auto it = mm.find(10);

Returns iterator to first matching key.

Example:

if(it != mm.end())
{
    cout << it->second;
}

Complexity:

O(log n)

-----------------------------------------

9. count()
----------

mm.count(10);

Returns:

Number of elements having key 10.

Example:

10 -> A
10 -> B
10 -> C

count(10) = 3

Interview Q:
Difference between map::count() and multimap::count()?

Answer:
map returns either 0 or 1, while multimap may return any number because duplicate keys are allowed.

-----------------------------------------

10. equal_range()
-----------------

Most Important Function.

Returns:

All elements having a key.

Example:

auto range = mm.equal_range(10);

for(auto it = range.first;
    it != range.second;
    ++it)
{
    cout << it->second << endl;
}

Interview Q:
How do you retrieve all values for a duplicate key?

Answer:
Use equal_range().

-----------------------------------------

11. lower_bound()
-----------------

Returns first element:

key >= given key

Example:

mm.lower_bound(10);

-----------------------------------------

12. upper_bound()
-----------------

Returns first element:

key > given key

Example:

mm.upper_bound(10);

-----------------------------------------

13. erase()
-----------

Erase all entries with key:

mm.erase(10);

Complexity:

O(log n + count)

-----------------------------------------

14. Iterating Multimap
----------------------

for(auto &p : mm)
{
    cout << p.first
         << " "
         << p.second
         << endl;
}

Output remains sorted by key.

-----------------------------------------

15. multimap vs map
-------------------

map
---
Unique keys

multimap
--------
Duplicate keys allowed

-----------------------------------------

16. multimap vs unordered_multimap
----------------------------------

multimap
--------
Red-Black Tree
Sorted
O(log n)

unordered_multimap
------------------
Hash Table
Not Sorted
Average O(1)

Interview Q:
Difference between multimap and unordered_multimap?

Answer:
multimap maintains sorted order using a Red-Black Tree, whereas unordered_multimap uses hashing and does not maintain order.

-----------------------------------------

